        <item>
          <title>ods-color-gradient: Number of classes</title>
          <link>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-color-gradient/#ods-color-gradient-number-of-classes</link>
          
            <pubDate>Fri, 30 Jul 2021 15:45:20 +0200</pubDate>
          
          
          <guid>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-color-gradient/#ods-color-gradient-number-of-classes</guid>
          <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;ods-color-gradient-nb-classes&lt;/code&gt; optional parameter defines the number of groups of values.
If not defined, colors will then NOT be grouped, and the corresponding legend will be a linear gradient.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Note: without classes, it&amp;rsquo;s a simple linear or pow color gradient&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Note 2: the more classes you have, the more it looks like a linear color gradient&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
</description>
        </item>
      
        <item>
          <title>ods-color-gradient: Power exponent</title>
          <link>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-color-gradient/#ods-color-gradient-power-exponent</link>
          
            <pubDate>Fri, 30 Jul 2021 15:45:20 +0200</pubDate>
          
          
          <guid>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-color-gradient/#ods-color-gradient-power-exponent</guid>
          <description>&lt;p&gt;The power exponent is used to create a power based scale.
The transform applied to value is of the type &lt;code&gt;y = x^k&lt;/code&gt; where &lt;code&gt;k&lt;/code&gt;, the exponent, can be any real number.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;For &lt;code&gt;k = 0.3&lt;/code&gt; : it approximates log scale.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;For &lt;code&gt;k = 1&lt;/code&gt; : it is a linear scale.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;For &lt;code&gt;k &amp;gt;= 2&lt;/code&gt; : it approximates square scale.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;ods-color-gradient-pow-exponent&lt;/code&gt; optional parameter defines the scale. If not defined, it will be set to 1 that correspond to a linear scale.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        </item>
      
        <item>
          <title>ods-legend: CSS tricks</title>
          <link>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-color-gradient/#ods-legend-css-tricks</link>
          
            <pubDate>Fri, 30 Jul 2021 15:45:20 +0200</pubDate>
          
          
          <guid>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-color-gradient/#ods-legend-css-tricks</guid>
          <description>&lt;p&gt;With some CSS, ods-legend can be horizontal. It can also be positioned on top of the map, to save space.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        </item>
      
        <item>
          <title>ods-legend: Display mode</title>
          <link>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-color-gradient/#ods-legend-display-mode</link>
          
            <pubDate>Fri, 30 Jul 2021 15:45:20 +0200</pubDate>
          
          
          <guid>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-color-gradient/#ods-legend-display-mode</guid>
          <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;display&lt;/code&gt; optional parameter can be &lt;code&gt;linear&lt;/code&gt; or &lt;code&gt;steps&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Note: &lt;code&gt;ods-color-gradient-nb-classes&lt;/code&gt; parameter is mandatory in order to use ods-legend widget in &lt;code&gt;steps&lt;/code&gt; mode&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
</description>
        </item>
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
    
      
      
        <item>
          <title>Lighten &#34;display-values&#34;</title>
          <link>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-chart-css-hacks/#lighten-display-values</link>
          
            <pubDate>Thu, 29 Jul 2021 10:00:10 +0200</pubDate>
          
          
          <guid>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-chart-css-hacks/#lighten-display-values</guid>
          <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;display-values=true&lt;/code&gt; option displays for each point of a chart the values of the series.
It&amp;rsquo;s usefull but can quickly overload the chart and displaying only a view values can be interesting.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This code presents some CSS tricks to cherry-pick only a few values :&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;On the left, only the first and last values&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;On the right, 1 out of 3 values are displayed (see the CSS code for explanations)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</description>
        </item>
      
    
      
      
        <item>
          <title>Get the oldest (min) and newest (max) date in a field</title>
          <link>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-adv-analysis/#get-the-oldest-min-and-newest-max-date-in-a-field</link>
          
            <pubDate>Thu, 12 Aug 2021 10:00:00 +0200</pubDate>
          
          
          <guid>https://codelibrary.opendatasoft.com/widget-tricks/ods-adv-analysis/#get-the-oldest-min-and-newest-max-date-in-a-field</guid>
          <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;min&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;max&lt;/code&gt; function can also work on date format field. It&amp;rsquo;s very useful to get the date range covered by the dataset on a specific field.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It can for example be used to initialise an &lt;code&gt;ods-date-range-slider&lt;/code&gt; with the correct bounds.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://help.opendatasoft.com/widgets/#/api/ods-widgets.directive:odsDateRangeSlider&#34;&gt;ods-date-range-slider documentation&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
        </item>
      
    
